Now, a careful comparison between the two authors, where they deal with the same or similar topics, reveals the fact that there is but a single passage in the Germania which can be said to betray the direct influ- . ence of Caesar,¹ for tbe few other verbal coincidenaes² per· tain to statements which would naturally be expressed in but one way. Other items of information exhibit either noteworthy dr'rerqences or amplificatione of so significant a character as to preclude Caesar as the direct or even the ulti- mate source of Tacitus on the subjecta in question. In fact, the wealth of new details and the very nature of the mate· rial in the Germania bear eloquent testimony to the advenae made in the geographical and ethnological knowledge of Germany since Caesar's time. Caesar, it cannot but be admitted, had at best only a superficial acquaintance with Germanic tribes, an acquaintance, mor-cover, acquired under one-sided conditions, for their most characteristic customs, ceremonias, and modes of life could only be observed in times of peace. A considerable part of the information which he furnished on these subjecta wne, therefore, nec- essarily secured at second hand. Nay, it can even still be shown that Caesar had himself occasionally consulted earlier literarp sources³ which were, of course, equally accessible tc Tacitus.
